the digital age, cultural commentary has become dumbed down and fragmented into niche markets. Mattias Freu, arguing against these claims, examines the history of film critical discourse in France, Germany, the United Kingdom, and the United States . He demonstrates that since its origins, film criticism has always found itself in crisis: the need to show critical authority and the anxieties over challenges to that authority have been longstanding concerns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aFilm criticism, critical authority, digital, journalism, historical analysis, new media.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066293140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048524471zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048524471zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048524471/original  a978-3-11-066293-1 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA